<subSubSection id="838827451276870E2673FE2B74C81E65" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" type="excursus: the tramp-species-supercolony syndrome in plagiolepis">
<paragraph id="8EDAD763434E118A5E07F57EF0E791F1" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">
Excursus: The tramp-species-supercolony syndrome in 
<taxonomicName id="83338C8B8957AC93B512B9D6480E6B88" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E5A782F65D63AFAC0830BDF14F9CC1E0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Plagiolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2FA072049FA9000CD1848A84281EF1CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">
<taxonomicName id="FB850F5254B2CD49E9ADA3C266692F7F" authorityName="Bernhard" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis invadens" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invadens">
<emphasis id="488BDE010B59F09D3151F2E804256CFE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Plagiolepis invadens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is, together with 
<taxonomicName id="95927AA3C1D14F8A8217F47E8C0E2BE8" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. schmitzii" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="schmitzii">
<emphasis id="BBB0DF9FD3DB1636E4226182FEEF4E9D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. schmitzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="212648D3905D113B1F7A8BCCA32618C7" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. pygmaea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis id="ABAE09A240470A4B21A943B0B3FAF6D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the third 
<taxonomicName id="AC24EE4D3157D99428FCCAE917F4FFA9" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="91298105DA7AD0D3B31A89C8038043A7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Plagiolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known from areas north of the Alps to show anthropogenous introduction, supercoloniality and permanent outdoor nesting throughout the year. The situation in 
<taxonomicName id="0947E27BA7951888176C2DAF5EDC2152" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. schmitzii" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="schmitzii">
<emphasis id="A0ACEC635C95CD853C74A07AB076D699" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. schmitzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is commented in the species chapter above and is not entirely new, but the case of 
<taxonomicName id="0F1F23F32BC1207CA1E463060666EF71" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. pygmaea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis id="732194F87362DAB6B17021728777134A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with an apparently new dynamics towards supercoloniality in introduction areas needs commentary. According to samples sent to me during last the three decades and deposited in SMN 
<normalizedToken id="2644AFE1A1D6F6B9F93BD10130AE05C7" originalValue="Görlitz">Goerlitz</normalizedToken>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D62E032676EC72B849B02452E05C0B43" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. pygmaea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis id="D489D59B1E13A0826E19C5749C2A8257" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been anthropogenously introduced to settlements and inner urban areas - most of these are situated far north of its natural range. The first year of observation and localities are 1993 in Mainz-Hechtsheim (
<geoCoordinate id="E1D4CF82487B3FDFE0278CBC9647BB2F" degrees="49.97" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="49.97">49.97°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="B40F2341239C375BB0A740C0A61C7CD3" degrees="8.27" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="8.27">8.27°E</geoCoordinate>
), 2007 in 
<normalizedToken id="5E931E6ECEA257EB66C279EF2BEC103F" originalValue="Berlin-Köpenick">Berlin-Koepenick</normalizedToken>
(
<geoCoordinate id="6A90C156C0EABF8BE589CB4F2BABFD11" degrees="52.49" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="52.49">52.49°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="5A36B6EDACD6F8DEAC2E54B8FFFE3100" degrees="13.57" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="13.57">13.57°E</geoCoordinate>
), 2011 in Hanhofen (
<geoCoordinate id="B87595ABCA48CFE42AD8E15B5822CB88" degrees="49.31" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="49.31">49.31°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="60E7CDC2DE44C7CD6C48EE02570EFEA1" degrees="8.34" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="8.34">8.34°E</geoCoordinate>
), 2019 in 
<normalizedToken id="1EB2D1C88182EA7928FAD7C334F16069" originalValue="Haßloch">Hassloch</normalizedToken>
(
<geoCoordinate id="A7DEF8EA32C105FDB3E53FD6EF293F2E" degrees="49.37" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="49.37">49.37°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="7920EA6930339502FACC76D52924CD56" degrees="8.24" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="8.24">8.24°E</geoCoordinate>
), 2019 in Zurich (
<geoCoordinate id="F63BD7D97B83868C4E4024EF37FC48B4" degrees="47.39" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="47.39">47.39°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="0435155D5C893543886487371C4E84B6" degrees="8.49" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="8.49">8.49°E</geoCoordinate>
) and 2020 in 
<normalizedToken id="469FB6E239BEB0C179E147785A6B5364" originalValue="Lützelsachsen">Luetzelsachsen</normalizedToken>
(
<geoCoordinate id="BC72AF57EF316890644981D1FB5B2706" degrees="49.52" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="49.52">49.52°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="8117A2EDE7E985B33E992A8DB86356DA" degrees="8.66" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="8.66">8.66°E</geoCoordinate>
). In three cases, introduction with plant material was apparent and, in the last two localities (Zurich and 
<normalizedToken id="F64CCD8AB5AA1F141F4C4A67CA329205" originalValue="Lützelsachsen">Luetzelsachsen</normalizedToken>
), the formation of supercolonies was observed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FCA884D8EFC6EE49CC6029FA4576883C" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">
Are there general traits or pre-adaptations in 
<taxonomicName id="EFB97E43E043DBCB39743245D2611E32" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2F5F07C09CC851DFFFC398B9F0C6AD5A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Plagiolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ants for a career as a tramp species, for eventual transformation to supercoloniality and for developing a competitive advantage - traits that might also explain the sudden emergence of 
<taxonomicName id="4463CCAF1E6F44AC33EFDAB3B03E911B" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. invadens" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="invadens">
<emphasis id="A93B4AE59D522FFE4EE9C270A51701F1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. invadens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. as if from nowhere? There are four 
<taxonomicName id="D4BA7952E89DA36AD143E1241FDE3AA8" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C8CFB5C55CE941AE1DF01555D892059F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Plagiolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with known mating scenarios and colony demography: the Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName id="16E4B6F802ABFBDE55FC9A9371D8B24B" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. pygmaea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis id="171D4044A7A457863FF8855331AEA025" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F4A749E8A2A9A32E1E33A3D2C5C2242D" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. taurica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="taurica">Pl. cf. taurica</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="57E1DC011B4280A519D603285535F744" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. schmitzii" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="schmitzii">
<emphasis id="E62AEA99AFC0268916DE84A300C9F550" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. schmitzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, studied by 
<bibRefCitation id="124CC1BF405ED8E668D1CB55E7D625FF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-294X.2011.05161.x" author="Thurin, N" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" pagination="3251 - 3260" refId="B19" refString="Thurin, N, Sery, N, Guimbretiere, R, Aron, S, 2011. Colony kin structure and breeding system in the ant genus Plagiolepis. Molecular Ecology 20: 3251 - 3260, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-294X.2011.05161.x" title="Colony kin structure and breeding system in the ant genus Plagiolepis." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-294X.2011.05161.x" volume="20" year="2011">Thurin et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7EA504E197A2FFC7616CE7C50F6614E4" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. alluaudi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="alluaudi">
<emphasis id="67373BE9EF79DAA7CAC854F7143FB6A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. alluaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Emery, 1894 from the tropics of the old world observed by 
<bibRefCitation id="1C4C12DAEBA0A8B36FAA93E50E3FB11A" author="Buschinger, A" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Insect Conservation" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" refId="B4" refString="Buschinger, A, 2012.: Plagiolepis alluaudi - aktuelle Informationen aus 2012. Ameisenwiki, online at [Accessed 7 July 2020]" title=": Plagiolepis alluaudi - aktuelle Informationen aus 2012. Ameisenwiki, online at [Accessed 7 July 2020]" year="2012">Buschinger (2012)</bibRefCitation>
in greenhouses of the Darmstadt Botanical Garden. All four species share characters facilitating anthropogenous introduction and transition to supercoloniality: (a) very small size, (b) wide food spectrum, (c) strong tendency for intranidal mating and (d) high degree of polygyny. A single medium-sized flower pot allows long-term survival and reproduction of these tiny ants and, placed at the right spot, it may serve as a beach head for supercolony formation by nest splitting.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="008D275BAD65F4B9AFE5D51B6EA4B8A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">
Another factor is probably also important for the success of 
<taxonomicName id="DA77C3C8FAD02D550EA2B7941B61B15A" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9241004EEED86D54D645D3E5A822A417" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Plagiolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ants. At least for 
<taxonomicName id="5F0DFF802DC825E7E392BDB779092E13" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. taurica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="taurica">
<emphasis id="4DD2F6F5E2D879FFB595CD2ADF823E1B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we have direct observations that an unidentified secretion emitted from the gaster tip is extremely toxic and repellent to other ant species (
<bibRefCitation id="83A33F9D5E4C46C3B0FAF294F989C479" author="Seifert, B" journalOrPublisher="Lutra Verlags- und Vertriebsgesellschaft, Tauer" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" refId="B14" refString="Seifert, B, 2018. The Ants of Central and North Europe. Lutra Verlags- und Vertriebsgesellschaft, Tauer" title="The Ants of Central and North Europe." year="2018">Seifert 2018</bibRefCitation>
) and which may explain that it is tolerated within the territories of dominant ants. 
<taxonomicName id="7D5A18B65E5DF427EE30205158812E44" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. taurica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="taurica">
<emphasis id="07EB4F4CA2A4432366CF8003181C6999" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may share a bait or trophobiont colony with so-called dominant ants or even displace these. These observations are repeated in other species: 
<taxonomicName id="49E49A6F1E268F2459111C5A68D33BB4" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. pygmaea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis id="78571DC101D850F6C5296ED7B80668AF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the only ant species allowed to co-exist and move freely within the territory of a 
<taxonomicName id="6EEBB54D6D642BC739CC5311C6F71257" baseAuthorityName="Mayr" baseAuthorityYear="1868" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Linepithema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Linepithema humile" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humile">
<emphasis id="1F3C0FE79CABF08CCBB1A5EF90206CA2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Linepithema humile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Mayr, 1868) supercolonies in France and Spain (
<bibRefCitation id="841FB40A86C09CB025B0159E98135601" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00040-020-00762-9" author="Charrier, NP" journalOrPublisher="Insectes Sociaux" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" pagination="331 - 335" refId="B5" refString="Charrier, NP, Bonsergent, C, Charrier, M, Malandrin, L, Kaufmann, B, Gippet, JMW, 2020. Invasive in the North: new latitudinal record for Argentine ants in Europe. Insectes Sociaux 67: 331 - 335, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s00040-020-00762-9" title="Invasive in the North: new latitudinal record for Argentine ants in Europe." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00040-020-00762-9" volume="67" year="2020">Charrier et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="E0A61EE2ED876B8D1C49956A7CE25F6F" family="Formicidae" genus="Pl." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pl. alluaudi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" rank="species" species="alluaudi">
<emphasis id="7B3A34806FADF894965E9A09335AFF0F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pl. alluaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was observed in the Bermudas (
<bibRefCitation id="65237B9F687E40A319CEC85CCA689801" author="Smith, MR" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the New York Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" pagination="195 - 198" refId="B18" refString="Smith, MR, 1957.: A contribution to the taxonomy, distribution and biology of the vagrant ant, Plagiolepis alluaudi Emery (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Journal of the New York Entomological Society 65: 195 - 198" title=": A contribution to the taxonomy, distribution and biology of the vagrant ant, Plagiolepis alluaudi Emery (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)." volume="65" year="1957">Smith 1957</bibRefCitation>
), New Caledonia (
<bibRefCitation id="02B9FC493E6CFDD0B1491D6CBFD23450" author="Le Breton, J" journalOrPublisher="Universite de Toulouse III, Toulouse, France" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" refId="B8" refString="Le Breton, J, 2003. Etude des interactions entre la fourmi Wasmannia auropunctata et la myrmecofaune. Comparison d'une situation en zone d'introduction: la Nouvelle-Caledonie et d'une situation en zone d'origine: la Guyane Francaise. Thesis. Universite de Toulouse III, Toulouse, France" title="Etude des interactions entre la fourmi Wasmannia auropunctata et la myrmecofaune. Comparison d'une situation en zone d'introduction: la Nouvelle-Caledonie et d'une situation en zone d'origine: la Guyane Francaise. Thesis." year="2003">Le Breton 2003</bibRefCitation>
) and the Great Barrier Reef islands (
<bibRefCitation id="C08C1277A1574DE5596C3520D89F24E0" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10841-012-9463-6" author="Burwell, CJ" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Insect Conservation" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" pagination="777 - 789" refId="B3" refString="Burwell, CJ, Nakamura, A, McDougall, A, Neldner, VJ, 2012. Invasive African big-headed ants, Pheidole megacephala, on coral cays of the southern Great Barrier Reef: distribution and impacts on other ants. Journal of Insect Conservation 16: 777 - 789, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10841-012-9463-6" title="Invasive African big-headed ants, Pheidole megacephala, on coral cays of the southern Great Barrier Reef: distribution and impacts on other ants." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10841-012-9463-6" volume="16" year="2012">Burwell et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
) to show, in contrast to other ants, no population decrease in the presence of dominant supercolonial 
<taxonomicName id="95EBD237E100CB3C24B6F0CE84743BCD" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1793" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole megacephala" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="183" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacephala">
<emphasis id="A73A828C2323D2E9152A7F800C823A55" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="183">Pheidole megacephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fabricius, 1793).
</paragraph>
